Romanian

[edit]

Etymology

[edit]

Borrowed from Hungarian mozsár, from German Mörser.

Noun

[edit]

mojar n (plural mojare)

  1. mortar (for grinding)
    Synonym: piuliță

Declension

[edit]
singular plural
indefinite definite indefinite definite
nominative-accusative mojar mojarul mojare mojarele
genitive-dative mojar mojarului mojare mojarelor
vocative mojarule mojarelor

See also

[edit]
  • mortar

Spanish

[edit]

Etymology

[edit]

Inherited from Vulgar Latin *molliāre (“soak”), a verb based on Latin mollis (“soft”). Compare Catalan mullar, Portuguese molhar, French mouiller.

Pronunciation

[edit]
  • IPA(key): /moˈxaɾ/ [moˈxaɾ]
  • Audio (Colombia):(file)
  • Rhymes: -aɾ
  • Syllabification: mo‧jar

Verb

[edit]

mojar (first-person singular present mojo, first-person singular preterite mojé, past participle mojado)

  1. (transitive, reflexive) to make wet, to wet
  2. (transitive) to dip (+ en)
  3. (transitive) to toast (celebrate with a drink)
    Synonym: brindar
